# TESS Program G07179

Title: Precision Exoplanet Transits For The Brightest Stars Using TESS 20-Second Cadence Data

PI: Huber, Daniel - University Of Hawaii (Manoa)

Type: SMALL

Summary: An key innovation of the first TESS extended mission was the introduction of 20-second data, which shows up to 30% better photometric precision than 2-minute data for bright stars due to differences in cosmic ray rejection algorithms. We propose to use 20-second data to improve transit parameters for all bright (T<10mag) TESS Objects of Interest and search for small planets around the brightest stars that may have been missed using 2-minute data in the prime mission. Our program will yield improved radii and orbital eccentricities for several key exoplanet systems, and may lead to the detection of a transiting planet around the brightest star to date.
